        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Commit-vs-Observe: The Core Tradeoff"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Plan-Then-Act commits to a full sequence before any execution begins. Interleaved planning runs exactly one planning cycle before each step \u2014 or a small look-ahead window \u2014 then observes the result before planning the next step. This turns execution into a tight observe-plan-act loop that can incorporate real-world feedback at every decision point."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Plan-Then-Act vs Interleaved Planning",
          "title": ""
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "In Plan-Then-Act, a failure at step 3 leaves steps 4 and 5 planned against assumptions that may now be invalid. Interleaved planning never plans step N+1 until step N's result is known, so the plan always reflects current world state."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
